### Fetch logs

Logs are fetched in DQL using the `fetch logs` command. Try it!

**Exercise:** Run the below DQL query.

**Exercise 2:** Try to adjust the timeframe in the query, and run it again.

Fetch documentation: https://docs.dynatrace.com/docs/shortlink/data-source-commands#fetch

Fetch logs can also be enhanced by the following operations:
* Add a timeframe (either relative or specific timestamps)
* Set a sampling ratio
* Set a ScanLimitGBytes (Upper limit - stop reading after X amount of data)

These options are automatically suggested. If the autocomplete doesn't show up, press control+spacebar while editing a DQL query.

### Fields

A lot of fun can be had with fields. It's similar to the **eval** command if you're used to splunk.

We have the following options:
* fieldsAdd - create a new field, add it to the existing set
* fieldsRemove - remove the specified fields
* fieldsKeep - keep the specified fields, remove everything else
* fields - A combination of **fieldsAdd** and **fieldsKeep**

**Exercise 1:** Try fetching logs, and only keep the fields `timestamp` , `content` and `process.technology`.

**Exercise 2:** Add a new field, that has value `true` when the field `process.technology` contains Java. As process.technology is an array, use the `in()` function to check if it contains Java.

Fields documentation: https://docs.dynatrace.com/docs/shortlink/selection-and-modification-commands
In documentation: https://docs.dynatrace.com/docs/shortlink/general-functions#in

### Filter

We've learned how to fetch data and how to manipulate it and view specific columns.

But all this data isn't the data we are interested in - we can fix that by using `filter`.

With **filter** we can do the following things:
* Filter for a specific log source (**index** if you're coming from splunk)
* Filter based on content in the log files
* Filter based on your own complex conditions

**Exercise 1:** Filter the data on `status == "ERROR"`

**Exercise 2:** Add another filter, this time `k8s.deployment.name == "headlessloadgen-*"`

**Exercise 3:** Instead of filtering on ERROR, filter on everything **except** error. Is there a special command for that?

Filter documentation: https://docs.dynatrace.com/docs/shortlink/filtering-commands

When filtering on log data, a few criteria can be very useful to quickly find what you want:

* For things that aren't in the cloud, dt.host_group.id and log.source will quickly narrow down what you are looking for.
* For searching in content, you can use these functions:
  * contains(content,"whatimlookingfor")
  * matchesPhrase(content,"thisiswhatIwanttosee")
  * matchesValue(content,"\*interesting\*")

---

Note that larger contents to search through will increase query times.

Searches through content do not benefit from data warping - combine these with other filters.

### Sort

Data in DQL is typically not sorted when accessed - this often doesn't matter.

To calculate the number of hits in the last hour, we don't need to sort it.

To sort very large datasets can take quite some time - so we only sort when it is specified.

We can sort using the `sort` command, and can sort ascending and descending. We can also sort based on multiple fields.

**Exercise:** Sort the data by timestamp, descending.

Sort documentation: https://docs.dynatrace.com/docs/shortlink/ordering-commands#sort

### Fetch Entities

We can also access entities in Grail, using the ```fetch dt.entity.*``` command, with * being the specific type that you want to fetch.

We only show the name + entity-ID by default, you can fetch the other relationships by using the `describe` command to view other options.

Describe documentation: https://docs.dynatrace.com/docs/shortlink/data-source-commands#describe

# Timeseries

We can also chart Timeseries using Grail. We do that with the `timeseries` command.

The `timeseries` syntax is different compared to what we are used to for now.

Once the timeseries is fetched, we can still use normal DQL commands such as `filter`.

**Exercise:** Chart the average host cpu using the 'Explore Metrics' feature.

**Exercise:** Chart the average host cpu using the timeseries command. 

Timeseries documentation: https://docs.dynatrace.com/docs/shortlink/metric-commands

Note that timeseries / metrics on Grail are still in Early Adopter and not GA yet.

### Limit

Sometimes we want to limit how much data is retrieved. 

We might be running a very expensive or slow query (e.g. 3 months of data) and want it to return as soon as it has some useful results. Or we want to get more than the default 1000 results. 

We can do so using the `limit` command.

**Exercise 1:** try to retrieve 10, 100, 1000 and 10000 logs using `limit`. What happens to the response size & data scanned? What happens if you start to add more filters?

**Exercise 2:** Which query is better?

```
fetch logs
| filter status == "ERROR"
| limit 10
```

```
fetch logs
| limit 10
| filter status == "ERROR"
```
